The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, January 02, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Jan. 1: The government announced revisions and modifications in the operative guidelines for foreign currency convertible bonds (FCCB) under which amounts over $50 million would be permitted only for financing import of equipment and foreign exchange needs of infrastructure projects. An official release said amendments have been made to the scheme for issue of FCCBs and ordinary shares (through depository receipts mechanism), 1993. 																								 New Delhi, Jan. 1: Domestic motorcycle makers reported higher sales in December. Hero Honda Motors registered a 28 per cent sales growth in December to 1.60 lakh units. Bajaj bike sales went up 3.77 per cent to 71,606 units.																								 Mumbai, Jan. 1: National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development (Nabard) today launched a fully-owned company, Nabard Consultancy Services Pvt Ltd, with a plan to generate an annual consultancy business of about Rs 15-20 crore from 2005-06.																								 New Delhi, Jan. 1: The Central Electricity Regulatory Authority today issued draft regulations for tariff-setting, proposing competitive bidding for power projects, in a move towards a regime of lighter regulation.																								 Mumbai, Jan 1: Goldstone Technologies has approved preferential equity warrants and shares to foreign investors to raise up to $15 million.
